entry.title: Lacros proxy tracker: Send extension metadata on extension loaded
entry.content:
The Lacros proxy tracker sends updates to Ash with metadata describing

the extension which is controlling the proxy pref. Ash uses this

metadata to populate the network settings UI.



There are a few cases where the Lacros proxy tracker receives proxy pref

updates but the extension which is controlling the proxy is not yet

loaded:

- A new Chrome session is started, where the extension has set the proxy

pref in a previous session;

- Ash to Lacros profile migration;

- Disabling and then enabling an extension which is controlling the

proxy.



This happens because the ExtensionPrefs KeyedService is parsing the extension-set pref values from the user pref kExtensions and setting it into the extensions pref store before the extension are loaded. The user pref kExtensions is stored in the Preferences file and read from disk when the PrefService is created.



For the last two cases, Ash never receives the extension metadata.



This CL adds an observer for RegistryEvents in the Lacros proxy tracker

to retry sending the extension metadata when the extension is ready.



Bug: b/293845404, b/290184836

entry.title: views: Handle ET_MOUSE_ENTERED in Widget and RootView
entry.content:
When running interactive_ui_tests on Linux ozone/wayland, it can happen

that the compositor only sends a "mouse enter" event that isn't

immediately followed by a "mouse motion" event. This results in only a

ET_MOUSE_ENTERED event being sent to Widget. However, both Widget and

RootView currently don't handle this type of event, which can lead to

test failures (see the related bug for more details).



We should handle enter events the same as other event types. This CL

implements this handling by reusing the code that handles ET_MOUSE_MOVED

events, because we need to set up `mouse_move_handler_` and synthesize

enter and exit events in the same way; the only difference is that we

don't send an ET_MOUSE_MOVED event to `mouse_move_handler_` when we're

handling an ET_MOUSE_ENTERED event.



Fixed: 1472995

entry.title: Sync ProfileTokenQuality observations.
entry.content:
For every stored type, AutofillProfile::token_quality() stores a set of

up to 10 observations. An observation consist of an ObservationType,

which is the value of a small enum, and a 1 byte hash used for some

deduplication.

This CL adds logic to sync these observations for account profiles. For

local-or-syncable profiles, observations won't be synced. For details,

see [1].



Technically, this CL:

- Adds a repeated Observation field to the

ContactInfoSpecifics::TokenMetadata proto.

- Modifies the AutofillProfile <-> ContactInfoSpecifics conversion logic

to populate the new field and convert back to AutofillProfile.



To keep the hash private, the conversion logic is made a friend of

ProfileTokenQuality.



To support future ProfileTokenQuality::ObservationTypes, the observation

types are stored as ints in the proto. Since the C++ side enum is an

enum class, unknown values will be preserved.



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-hoBeCogz8gewu3rfhRNGTWObqWfwSSNZ29ikYGml2I/edit?resourcekey=0-vK0gJwbg5cmepJJHBGCC7g

entry.title: Remove StrictModeContext from the input Hot path on Android.
entry.content:
StrictModeContext was added due to developers using WebView encountering

the violation of a NonSDK usage. However we have noticed as this rolled

out that suppressing the error at run time results in a 1ms increase of

all input event handling at the median, and 2.1ms at the 95th

percentile.



This is too expensive to accept for input events which can come once

every 4ms on 120Hz devices. Thus reverse the suppression.



This means that on Android P to Android T (API level 28 to 33) this

strict mode violation will be reported, and down stream apps should add

it to their ignore list. In Android U this function was added to the

public API and thus the violation no longer occurs.

entry.title: Workaround: reset self update delay iff the registration is available.
entry.content:
In crbug.com/1475465, we observe the crash due to lack of the live

registration. We believe that when there is a ServiceWorkerVersion,

it should always have an associated live registration. However, the

linked crbug looks not and caused the crash due to null pointer

assignment.



We intend to duct-taping the code to mitigate the crash. At the same

time, we wonder if it may bring a security issue. Our conclusion is no.

Considering what this code do, it reset the update timer so that the

update of the ServiceWorker do not hit the timeout. If the reset

happens where it should not be, update would never finish. That is what

a CL that added the code originally wanted to do (See:

https://crrev.com/c/900763). This CL makes the reset happen iff the live

registration is available, and it reduces the risk to keep the update

running.

entry.title: MaybeCommitResponse() can commit while State::kDataTransferStarted
entry.content:
Before this CL, once MaybeCommitResponse() is called, it sets

State::kResponseCommitted, and any states other than kResponseReceived

are guarded. This means the core logic of MaybeCommitResponse() is

executed only once.



However, when ServiceWorkerAutoPreload is enabled, this behavior is

problematic because AutoPreload may update the commit responsibility

from the fetch handler to the network request when fallback, and this

may happen while teeing the response data, which involves multiple

MaybeCommitResponse() calls. Actually this is very rare case but this is

the root cause of the test flakiness[1].



This CL fixes this issue by introducing the new state called

kDataTransferStarted. This is the State between kResponseReceived and

kResponseCommitted.



[1] https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/android-nougat-x86-rel/370942/overview

entry.title: PA: Rework `PartitionOptions`
entry.content:
This CL is intended to be trivial. It collapses the individual enums

defined by `PartitionOptions` into two general-purpose enums: the

"allow" toggle and the "enable" toggle.



With the prevailing use of designated initializers to construct

`PartitionOptions`, the existing



```

.foo = PartitionOptions::FooSetting::kEnabled,

.bar = PartitionOptions::BarSetting::kAllowed,

```



Can now be rewritten to a shorter form:



```

.foo = PartitionOptions::kEnabled,

.bar = PartitionOptions::kAllowed,

```



There is a modest trade-off in type safety, as future changes to

`PartitionRoot` could potentially read a compatible enum from the wrong

member of `PartitionOptions`. Hopefully, such mistakes would be caught

by code review.

within the grid sizing algorithm we assumed that the resolved size

for both axes should stretch to the containing grid area, regardless

function for computing the intrinsic sizes of a subgrid.

this CL migrates `PrefetchStreamingURLLoader::status_`

into already-introduced `PrefetchResponseReader::load_state_`
